In [5]:
# Step 3: Preprocessing Data
df['win'] = df['win'].astype(int)
df['mac'] = df['mac'].astype(int)
df['linux'] = df['linux'].astype(int)

rating_encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)
rating_encoded = rating_encoder.fit_transform(df[['rating']])

df_rating_encoded = pd.DataFrame(rating_encoded, columns=rating_encoder.categories_)
df = pd.concat([df.drop('rating', axis=1), df_rating_encoded], axis=1)

# Normalize the numerical features
scaler = StandardScaler()
df[['positive_ratio', 'user_reviews', 'price_final']] = scaler.fit_transform(df[['positive_ratio', 'user_reviews', 'price_final']])

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Ensure you have the correct matplotlib backend set up for your environment if you are not using Jupyter Notebooks.
%matplotlib inline

# Load the data
df = pd.read_csv('games.csv')

# Convert 'date_release' to datetime and extract the year
df['date_release'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date_release'], errors='coerce')
df['release_year'] = df['date_release'].dt.year

# Plot a histogram of the games released by year (Past Games)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.histplot(df['release_year'].dropna(), bins=30, kde=False)
plt.title('Distribution of Games Released Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Games Released')
plt.show()

# Boxplot for game prices
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=df[['price_final', 'win', 'mac', 'linux']])
plt.title('Distribution of Game Prices Across Platforms')
plt.ylabel('Price Final')
plt.show()


# Plot New Games released in the last year in the dataset (New Games)
current_year = df['release_year'].max()
new_games = df[df['release_year'] == current_year]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x='user_reviews', y='title', data=new_games.head(10))
plt.title(f'Top New Games by User Reviews in {current_year}')
plt.xlabel('Number of User Reviews')
plt.ylabel('Game Title')
plt.show()

# Example of a time series plot for game releases over time
game_releases_by_year = df.groupby('release_year').size()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
game_releases_by_year.plot(kind='line')
plt.title('Number of Game Releases Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Games Released')
plt.show()

# Pivot table for ratings over time
ratings_pivot = df.pivot_table(index='release_year', columns='rating', values='app_id', aggfunc='count')
ratings_pivot.plot(kind='area', stacked=True, figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title('Game Ratings Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Games')
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load the data
df = pd.read_csv('games.csv')

# Convert 'user_reviews' to numeric in case it's stored as a string
df['user_reviews'] = pd.to_numeric(df['user_reviews'], errors='coerce')

# Sort the DataFrame by 'user_reviews' and take the top 10
top_10_popular_games = df.nlargest(10, 'user_reviews')

# Plotting the top 10 most popular games
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
sns.barplot(x='user_reviews', y='title', data=top_10_popular_games, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Top 10 Most Popular Games by User Reviews')
plt.xlabel('User Reviews')
plt.ylabel('Game Title')
plt.show()
